Supplements

Supplement 1: Confusion matrix and ROC curve of the analysed models in the internal evaluation.
Supplement 2: Confusion matrix and ROC curve of the analysed models in the external evaluation. 
Supplementary Table 1: Number and distribution of cases retrieved from each participating centre. 
Supplementary Table 2: Immunohistochemical and molecular profile of head and neck small, round and blue cell neoplasms.
Supplementary Table 3: TRIPOD-AI checklist.
Supplementary Table 4: STARD-AI checklist. 
Supplementary Table 5: Description of the dataset of this study.
Supplementary Table 6: Distribution of cases across the training, validation, test, and external validation cohorts according to biological tumour group. The dataset comprised 675 cases categorised as haematolymphoid (n = 463), neuroectodermal and neural crest-derived (n = 84), mesenchymal (n = 75), and melanocytic (n = 53) neoplasms. Cases were allocated to the training (70%), validation (10%), test (10%), and external validation (10%) cohorts whilst maintaining class balance. 


рџ”’ Data Availability

Due to ethical restrictions, institutional review board regulations, and patient privacy requirements, complete whole-slide images (WSIs), raw clinicopathological data, survival information, and patient-identifiable material cannot be publicly released.
Only representative examples, synthetic datasets, pretrained model configurations, and directory structures are provided to facilitate reproducibility of the computational pathology workflow.
Researchers interested in accessing the original data may contact the corresponding authors and obtain appropriate ethical approvals and data-sharing agreements from participating institutions.
